## Part 7: Auto-Sharpening

Same principle as weather: medium/high tier events (not tail) use the **current zone** to determine uncertainty width, not the zone at reveal time. As an event slides from zone D to zone C, its window automatically tightens.

The uncertainty window is recomputed at display time. **All internal math uses the raw fractional event serial from the sequence — rounding to integer day boundaries happens only at the final rendering step** (see Part 14: Precision for full details).

```typescript
function _moonEventUncertaintyWindow(eventSerial, moonName, moonPeriod, quality, zone, worldSeed) {
  // eventSerial is the RAW fractional serial from the sequence (e.g., 12345.73)
  if (quality <= 1) return { startDay: Math.floor(eventSerial), endDay: Math.ceil(eventSerial) }; // high tier: exact

  var fraction;
  if (zone === 'A' || zone === 'Ap') fraction = 20;
  else if (zone === 'B' || zone === 'Bp') fraction = 12;
  else if (zone === 'C') fraction = 6;
  else fraction = 4; // zone D

  // Fractional window width — no rounding yet
  var totalWidth = moonPeriod / fraction;

  // Per-event offset ratio (seeded, deterministic)
  var offsetSeed = hash(eventSerial, moonName, worldSeed, 'moon-offset');
  var offsetRatio = seededFloat(offsetSeed); // 0.0 to 1.0

  // Fractional padding — preserves full precision
  var leftPad = totalWidth * offsetRatio;
  var rightPad = totalWidth - leftPad;

  var startExact = eventSerial - leftPad;
  var endExact = eventSerial + rightPad;

  // Round to integer day boundaries ONLY for display.
  // Floor the start, ceil the end — guarantees the actual event
  // is always inside the displayed range.
  return {
    startDay: Math.floor(startExact),
    endDay: Math.ceil(endExact),
    // Preserve fractional values for any downstream computation
    startExact: startExact,
    endExact: endExact
  };
}
```

Tail events (A′/B′) use their fixed fraction — A′ always uses 1/20, B′ always uses 1/12 — regardless of which actual zone they’re currently in.

